-- China stocks close up sharply on further easing signals
-- 
-- Tue Nov 25, 2014 02:12AM EST
-- None



SHANGHAI, Nov 25 (Reuters) - China stocks closed up on Tuesday as domestic markets continued to rally after the central bank lowered a key short-term money rate, seen as a sign of continued easing. [ID:nL3N0TF1JS]

Foreign investment flowing from Hong Kong into Shanghai through the mutual market access pilot programme was tepid at 2.85 billion yuan ($464.12 million), slightly over one-fifth of the 13 billion yuan daily quota, after a strong rise on Monday, when offshore investors bought nearly 7 billion yuan worth of Chinese shares. The CSI300 index <.CSI300> of the largest listed companies in Shanghai and Shenzhen rose 1.4 percent, to 2,685.56, its highest level since Feb 2013, while the Shanghai Composite Index <.SSEC> also gained 1.4 percent, to 2,567.60 points, its highest level since 2011. Among the most active stocks in Shanghai were Zijin Mining <601899.SS>, up 5.62 percent to 2.82 yuan; Baotou Steel <600010.SS>, up 0.65 percent to 3.103.10 yuan; and Founder Securities <601901.SS>, up 3.32 percent to 8.40 yuan. In Shenzhen, BOE Technology <000725.SZ>, up 1.1 percent to 2.66 yuan; TCL Corp <000100.SZ>, up 0.9 percent to 3.28 yuan; and GF Securities <000776.SZ>, up 5.9 percent to 15.69 yuan, were among the most actively traded.